snippet.textDisplay:
Football is so different now to what it was in the 90s. It was all 442 in the 90s, so your wingers where more midfield players, not forwards like they are in modern football. Full backs played more as defenders, as there wasn’t a holding midfield player to help the centre backs out, allowing the full backs to get forward more.

Back in the 90s the Premier League was also a lot more competitive. The gap between the top and the bottom was a lot less. Modern day football the top sides have squads of 25 players who are all a lot better than any of the bottom sides. Where as back then the top sides didn’t have the squads, and these other quality players would be playing for the weaker sides rather than sitting on the bench for the top teams. So you’d never get teams getting 100 points, as the weaker sides where a lot stronger back then. This is what the money in the game has caused, so many good players happy to sit on the bench getting 150k a week, rather than play week in week out for a weaker side.

So it’s impossible to really compare the 2 sides on stats, as things where so different back then. The trophy’s a side wins are all you can really compare IMO. So we will have to wait and see how well this Liverpool side does in that respect.

snippet.textDisplay: Got no horse in this race as an Arsenal fan but I can't argue with Jamie choosing Mané over Giggs. Roy argues about consitency but since Mané has been at Liverpool he has, hands down, not only been their most consistent forward but also been the most reliable when it has come to big/important matches. Giggs had his influential moments but I struggle to think of a season when I would say that if it weren't for him that United wouldn't have won a particular trophy. Whereas, if it hadn't have been for Mané's performances last season then there's no way Liverpool would have got to the final let alone won the Champions League last year. In my opinion he should have won the Ballon D'or for last season.
